Given a directed container (S \triangleleft  P, o, \downarrow , \oplus ), and a monad container (T \triangleleft  Q, \iota , \sigma , \text {pr}) we define a comonad-monad container distributive law as given by the data:

       \begin {align*}            &u_2 : \prod _{s : S} \prod _{f : P\ s \to  T} Q\ (f\ (o\ \{s\})) \to  S \\     &v_1 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (f\ (o\ \{s\}))} P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q) \to  P\ s \\     &v_2 : \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  T\}} \prod _{q : Q\ (f\ (o\ \{s\}))} \prod _{p : P\ (u_2\ s\ f\ q)} Q\ (f\ (v_1\ q\ p)) \\        \end {align*}   

  where the following equalities hold:

       \begin {align*}            u_2\ s\ f\ q \downarrow  p &= u_2\ (s \downarrow  v_1\ q\ p)\ (\lambda  p' . f\ (v_1\ q\ p \oplus  p'))\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\     v_1\ q\ o &= o\\     v_1\ q\ (p \oplus  p') &= v_1\ q\ p \oplus  v_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\ p'\\     v_2\ q\ o &= q\\     v_2\ q\ (p \oplus  p') &= v_2\ (v_2\ q\ p)\ p'\\     \\     u_2\ s\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota )\ p &= s\\     v\ \{s\}\ \{\lambda  \_ . \iota \} &= \langle  \pi _2 , \pi _1 \rangle \\     u_2\ s\ (\sigma  \circ  \langle  f , g \rangle )\ q &= u_2\ (u_2\ s\ f\ (\text {pr}_1\ q))\ (\lambda  p . g\ (v_1\ q\ p)\ (v_2\ q\ p))\ (\text {pr}_2\ q)\\     v_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ q)\ p) &= v_1\ q\ p\\     v_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ q)\ (v_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ q)\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ (v_2\ q\ p)\\     v_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ q)\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (v_2\ q\ p)        \end {align*}

Let S \triangleleft  P be a container. A directed container [ahmanchapmanuustalu2012] on S \triangleleft  P is given by the following data:
       \begin {align*}       \downarrow  &: \prod _{s : S} P\ s \to  S\\       o &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} P\ s\\       \oplus  &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{p : P\ s} P\ (s \downarrow  p) \to  P\ s     \end {align*}   
  satisfying two shape equations and three position equations:
       \begin {align*}       s \downarrow  o &= s\\       s \downarrow  (p \oplus  p') &= (s \downarrow  p) \downarrow  p'\\       p \oplus  o &= p\\       o \oplus  p &= p\\       (p \oplus  p') \oplus  p'' &= p \oplus  (p' \oplus  p'')     \end {align*}

Let S \triangleleft  P be a container. A monad container (or mnd-container) [uustalu2017] on S \triangleleft  P is given by the following data:
       \begin {align*}       \iota  &: S\\       \sigma  &: \prod _{s : S} (P\ s \to  S) \to  S\\       \text {pr} &: \prod _{\{s : S\}} \prod _{\{f : P\ s \to  S\}} P\ (\sigma \ s\ f) \to  \sum _{p : P\ s} P\ (f\ p)     \end {align*}   
  For which the following laws hold:
       \begin {align*}       \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  \_ . \iota  ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_1\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ \iota \ (\lambda  \_ . a ) &= a\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= p\\       \sigma \ (\sigma \ a\ f)\ (\lambda  p . g\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)) &= \sigma \ a\ (\lambda  p . \sigma \ (f\ p)\ (g\ p))\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_1\ p) &= \text {pr}_1\ p\\       \text {pr}_1\ (\text {pr}_2\ p) &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_1\ p)\\       \text {pr}_2\ p &= \text {pr}_2\ (\text {pr}_2\ p)     \end {align*}   
  We abbreviate \pi _1 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_1 and \pi _2 \circ  \text {pr} as \text {pr}_2. Each set of laws for \text {pr} hold up to the laws for \sigma  above them.
